# Minesweeper environment configuration
#
# Copy this file to `.env` (gitignored) and adjust values as needed. Every
# variable below is optional — Minesweeper falls back to the default shown
# next to each key. Booleans accept: true/false, 1/0, yes/no, on/off.
#
# Configuration sources, in order of precedence (highest wins):
#   1. Environment variables in this file / your shell.
#   2. Per-repo JSON file at `<cwd>/.minesweeper/config.json` (overridable
#      via MINESWEEPER_REPO_CONFIG_FILE; see below).
#   3. Global JSON file at `~/.minesweeper/config.json` (overridable via
#      MINESWEEPER_CONFIG_FILE; see below).
#   4. Hard-coded defaults baked into `src/config.ts`.
#
# Note: `schedule` (cron expressions) is settable **only** via a JSON file —
# cron list fields contain commas which can't round-trip through an env var.
#
# The canonical schema lives in `src/config.ts`. If anything here drifts
# from that file, treat `src/config.ts` as the source of truth.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Upstream credentials
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Anthropic API key consumed by `@anthropic-ai/claude-agent-sdk`. Required
# unless the SDK is already authenticated via an existing Claude Code login
# on this machine. NOTE: If you have a Max or Pro plan, then LEAVE THIS UNSET,
# ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-...

# Personal access token used by the `gh` CLI when invoked by the
# orchestrator. If `gh auth login` has already been run, leave this unset.
# Either name works; `gh` prefers GH_TOKEN when both are present.
# GH_TOKEN=ghp_...
# GITHUB_TOKEN=ghp_...

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# GitHub App identity (optional — author PRs as a bot instead of you)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# When set, Minesweeper mints a GitHub App *installation token* and uses it
# for every `gh` call, the branch push, and the PR — so PRs are "opened by"
# the App's bot user and commits are authored by it, rather than by whoever
# runs the daemon. Leaving these unset keeps the ambient `gh`/git identity
# above (default behaviour). When set, the installation token takes
# precedence over GH_TOKEN / `gh auth login`.
#
# Setup:
#   1. Create a GitHub App (Settings → Developer settings → GitHub Apps) and
#      generate a private key (.pem).
#   2. Install it on the target repo(s) with these permissions:
#        Issues: Read & write          (issue comments + labels)
#        Pull requests: Read & write   (PR create + review comments/reactions)
#        Contents: Read & write        (branch push)
#        Metadata: Read                (mandatory)
#        Checks: Read                  (CI-feedback loop)
#        Code scanning alerts: Read    (only if alerts are eligible)
#        Secret scanning alerts: Read  (only if alerts are eligible)
#   3. Set the app id and key below. The installation id is resolved
#      automatically from the repo when omitted.
#
# Note: commits made via the git CLI show as "Unverified" — GitHub only
# auto-verifies App commits created through its Contents API.

# Numeric GitHub App id (App settings → "App ID").
# MINESWEEPER_GITHUB_APP_ID=123456

# Installation id. Optional — resolved from the repo via the API when unset.
# MINESWEEPER_GITHUB_APP_INSTALLATION_ID=987654

# The App private key. Prefer the PATH form (the inline PEM is fine too, but
# set only ONE of the two). The path form keeps the secret out of the daemon
# environment that is passed down to child processes.
# MINESWEEPER_GITHUB_APP_PRIVATE_KEY_PATH=/abs/path/to/minesweeper-ai-bot.private-key.pem
# MINESWEEPER_GITHUB_APP_PRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----\n...\n-----END RSA PRIVATE KEY-----"

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Eligibility / labels
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# When true, every issue is eligible unless explicitly excluded by label.
# When false (default), only issues with the always-fix label are eligible.
# MINESWEEPER_DEFAULT_ELIGIBLE=false

# Whether code-scanning and secret-scanning alerts are auto-eligible. Alerts
# cannot carry GitHub labels, so this is the only opt-in/out for them. When
# false, the daemon also stops calling the alert APIs (handy for repos
# without GitHub Advanced Security so you don't see 403s every poll).
# MINESWEEPER_ALERTS_ELIGIBLE=true

# Label that opts an issue *into* Minesweeper's queue.
# MINESWEEPER_ALWAYS_FIX_LABEL=autofix

# Label that opts an issue into Minesweeper's queue *and* sends it through
# the prompt-injection screener first. Use this for issues filed by users
# you trust less than yourself, or to dogfood the screener. Routes the same
# way the `MINESWEEPER_DEFAULT_ELIGIBLE=true` catch-all does — `dangerous`
# / `uncertain` verdicts get labelled `MINESWEEPER_POSSIBLY_DANGEROUS_LABEL`
# and skipped; `safe` proceeds to the planner.
# MINESWEEPER_TRY_FIX_LABEL=tryFix

# Label that opts an issue *out of* Minesweeper's queue.
# MINESWEEPER_NEVER_FIX_LABEL=manual

# Label applied when the eligibility screen flags possible prompt injection
# or other malicious content. Issues with this label are skipped until a
# human reviews them.
# MINESWEEPER_POSSIBLY_DANGEROUS_LABEL=possiblyDangerous

# Label a human applies after reviewing to indicate that the issue is safe.
# MINESWEEPER_MANUALLY_APPROVED_LABEL=manuallyReviewed

# Label applied when Minesweeper gives up on an issue after exhausting
# retries. Useful for filtering out repeat-failure issues.
# MINESWEEPER_FAILED_LABEL=minesweeperFailed

# Label applied to sub-issues that Minesweeper itself opens during
# assess/refine. Inherits the parent's always-fix label when the parent
# carries one.
# MINESWEEPER_SUBTASK_LABEL=subtask

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Agent / model selection
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Each value is a model alias passed through to the Claude Agent SDK
# (e.g. "haiku", "sonnet", "opus"). Pick faster/cheaper models for the
# eligibility screen and review pass; pick stronger models for planning
# and execution.

# Model used to screen incoming issues for eligibility + prompt injection.
# MINESWEEPER_ELIGIBILITY_AGENT=haiku

# Model used by the planner ↔ critic loop.
# MINESWEEPER_PLANNING_AGENT=claude-opus-4-7

# Model used by the reviewer during execution.
# MINESWEEPER_REVIEW_AGENT=claude-opus-4-6

# Model used by the executor (writes code, runs tests, opens the PR).
# MINESWEEPER_EXECUTION_AGENT=claude-opus-4-7

# Model used by `minesweeper issue new` to shape free-text input into a
# well-formed autofix issue body. Sonnet is the right default here — the
# job is structured rewriting, not deep reasoning.
# MINESWEEPER_ISSUE_WRITER_AGENT=claude-sonnet-4-6

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Execution loops
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Hard cap on planner ↔ critic round-trips before Minesweeper bails out
# of planning mode. Must be >= 1.
# MINESWEEPER_MAX_PLANNING_ITERATIONS=5

# Hard cap on executor ↔ reviewer round-trips before Minesweeper either
# ships what it has or gives up. Must be >= 1.
# MINESWEEPER_MAX_REVIEW_ROUNDS=3

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Worktree + git
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Directory under which Minesweeper materialises per-issue git worktrees.
# Absolute, or relative to the main repo. Each issue gets its own
# subdirectory; on success the parent removes it after archiving
# `.minesweeper/`.
# MINESWEEPER_WORKTREE_PATH=/tmp/minesweeper

# Branch used as the base for new pull requests opened by Minesweeper.
# MINESWEEPER_PR_BASE_BRANCH=main

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Daemon
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# How often the parent daemon polls GitHub for new eligible issues, in
# seconds. Minimum 30 (GitHub rate limits / API courtesy). Ignored when one
# or more cron `schedule` entries are set in the JSON config file.
# MINESWEEPER_POLL_INTERVAL_SECONDS=300

# Minimum number of seconds between successive poll ticks. Multiple
# overlapping schedules cannot trigger a tick inside this window — the
# second one is logged as "skipped poll: within cooldown" and dropped.
# Set to 0 to disable the gate entirely. Minimum 0.
# MINESWEEPER_POLL_COOLDOWN=120

# Path to the **global** JSON config file. Supplies cross-repo defaults and
# is one of the two places `schedule` can be set. Defaults to
# `~/.minesweeper/config.json`. Missing files are treated as empty.
# MINESWEEPER_CONFIG_FILE=~/.minesweeper/config.json

# Path to the **per-repo** JSON config file. Layered on top of the global
# file and overridden by environment variables. Defaults to
# `<cwd>/.minesweeper/config.json`, so each working tree carries its own
# overrides. Note: `.minesweeper/` is typically gitignored — to share repo
# settings with a team, add `!.minesweeper/config.json` as a gitignore
# exception, or point this variable at a committed path elsewhere. Missing
# files are treated as empty.
# MINESWEEPER_REPO_CONFIG_FILE=./.minesweeper/config.json

# Maximum number of issue children the daemon will run in parallel.
# v0 is single-threaded; concurrency lands in M3.
# MINESWEEPER_MAX_CONCURRENCY=1

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Prompt customisation
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Absolute path to a directory of override role prompts (planner.md,
# critic.md, executor.md, …). Leave unset (the default) to use the prompts
# bundled inside the installed minesweeper package — that's what you want
# for almost every deployment.
#
# To customise prompts for a single repo, run `minesweeper config prompts`
# from its root: it copies the bundled prompts to `.minesweeper/prompts/`
# and writes the absolute path into the per-repo config for you. Editing
# this env var directly is for advanced setups (e.g. shared prompts on a
# build server).
# MINESWEEPER_CUSTOM_PROMPTS_PATH=/abs/path/to/.minesweeper/prompts
